  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This large-scale community review of quantum computing applications in high-energy physics has accumulated 25 citations since its publication, establishing itself as a substantive reference point for researchers navigating the intersection of quantum information science and particle physics. Its presence across six open courseware platforms signals a growing pedagogical role that extends its reach well beyond the primary research community.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Authored by a notably broad consortium \u2014 with Alberto Di Meglio as corresponding author and more than 45 contributors drawn from institutions spanning Europe and North America, hosted at RWTH Aachen University \u2014 this work represents a coordinated community effort to map the current landscape of quantum computing as it applies to high-energy physics. The article is formally linked to a published version in PRX Quantum, making it both a preprint deposit and a peer-reviewed contribution, with green open-access availability ensuring wide readability. The sheer scale of its authorship reflects the collaborative ethos of the high-energy physics community, where large working groups regularly produce consensus documents of this kind.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work's citation count of 25 is its clearest indicator of scholarly uptake. Given that the article explicitly positions itself as a state-of-the-art review, it is unsurprising that subsequent work in this fast-moving field draws on it as a foundational reference. The reuse signal mirrors the citation count directly, consistent with a document that functions as a shared starting point \u2014 a map of where the field stands and where the open problems lie \u2014 rather than a narrowly focused experimental report.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Perhaps the most distinctive signal in this profile is the article's pedagogical footprint. Its subject matter appears in at least six open courseware contexts, spanning materials from MIT OpenCourseWare and the University of Tokyo, as well as broader courses addressing quantum thinking in applied and innovation design settings. This breadth suggests that instructors in both foundational quantum physics courses and more applied technology programs are directing students toward resources in this space, and that a well-structured review article fills a genuine gap in accessible teaching material at the frontier of quantum computing and fundamental physics.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">One area where the evidence remains thin is online public discourse: no tracked social media mentions or news events are registered in the available data, and download metrics through the repository record are not populated. This is not unusual for a highly technical review aimed at specialists, and it does not diminish the article's scholarly standing. The modest SDG alignment with affordable and clean energy \u2014 plausible given quantum computing's potential relevance to energy-efficient computation and materials simulation \u2014 adds a peripheral dimension to the work's broader significance, though this connection is exploratory rather than central to the article's own framing. Overall, the profile points to a work that is doing real intellectual work within its field: read, cited, and increasingly integrated into how the next generation of physicists and quantum engineers are being taught.</p>",
